%[text] # A02: Molecular Clustering  -- Grouping Compounds by Structural Similarity
%[text] EasyMolKit Analytics  -- Layer 3
%[text] A natural products chemist has isolated 30 compounds from food and household items. Before running bioactivity assays, grouping structurally similar compounds avoids redundant tests and reduces costs.
%[text] In this tutorial, we cluster molecules using Morgan ECFP4 fingerprints and Tanimoto distance, comparing hierarchical (Ward linkage) and k-means approaches.
%[text] ### What You Will Learn in This Tutorial
%[text] - Understand why fingerprints are used instead of descriptors for clustering
%[text] - Learn how to construct a Tanimoto matrix with `emk.similarity.matrix()`
%[text] - Understand how to convert Tanimoto similarity into a distance metric for hierarchical methods
%[text] - Learn how to use `linkage()` and `dendrogram()` from the Statistics Toolbox
%[text] - Learn how to evaluate cluster quality using MATLAB's `kmeans()` and `silhouette()`
%[text] - Learn how to interpret clustering results in a chemical context \
%[text] ### Prerequisites
%[text] - Completion of F03 (Fingerprints) and F04 (Similarity)
%[text] - Recommended: Understanding context from A01 (Chemical Space PCA)
%[text] - Use of Statistics and Machine Learning Toolbox (linkage, kmeans, silhouette)
%[text] - No internet connection required
%[text] - Estimated time required: 30-45 minutes \
%[text] ### Data: 
%[text] - `data/list/everyday_chemicals.csv`  -- 30 common molecules (PubChem CC0) \
%[text] ### References
%[text] - Willett P, Barnard JM, Downs GM (1998) Chemical similarity searching. J Chem Inf Comput Sci 38:983-996. doi:10.1021/ci9800211
%[text] - Rogers D & Hahn M (2010) Extended-connectivity fingerprints. J Chem Inf Model 50:742-754. doi:10.1021/ci100050t
%[text] - Ward JH (1963) Hierarchical grouping to optimise an objective function. J Am Stat Assoc 58:236-244. doi:10.1080/01621459.1963.10500845
%[text] - Kaufman L & Rousseeuw PJ (1990) Finding Groups in Data: An Introduction to Cluster Analysis. Wiley. (silhouette coefficient, Chapter 2) \
%[text] How to Run: Execute each section with Ctrl+Enter
%%
%[text] ## Section 0: Environment Setup
% Resolve project root (works for Desktop, MCP, and MATLAB Online)
sDir = fileparts(mfilename('fullpath'));
if strlength(sDir) > 0
    addpath(genpath(fullfile(sDir, '..', '..', '..', 'src')));
elseif isfolder(fullfile(pwd, 'src'))
    addpath(genpath(fullfile(pwd, 'src')));
elseif ~isempty(which("logInfo"))
    addpath(genpath(fileparts(fileparts(which("logInfo")))));
end
projectRoot = resolveProjectRoot();
addpath(genpath(fullfile(projectRoot, 'src')));
logSection("A02", "Section 0: Setup", "Analytics L3"); %[output:781d840b]
emk.setup.initPython(); %[output:494cab3b]
%[text] Warm up the Python/RDKit process before the main procedure.
mol_warmup = emk.mol.fromSmiles("C");   % Methane -- lightweight
clear mol_warmup;
%%
%[text] ## Section 1: Morgan Fingerprint Calculation for All Molecules
%[text] ### Why Use Fingerprints for Structural Clustering
%[text] Descriptors (such as molecular weight, LogP, TPSA, which quantify physicochemical properties) represent the "physical properties" of molecules.
%[text] However, when two molecules have similar physical properties but completely different scaffolds, descriptors alone cannot determine if they are "structurally similar."
%[text] Fingerprints encode the presence or absence of local substructures around each atom as a 0/1 bit string (binary vector).
%[text] Two molecules with the same scaffold will share many common bits even if their substituents differ, thus reflecting structural similarity not captured by descriptors.
%[text] ### How Morgan Fingerprint (ECFP4) Works
%[text] The Morgan algorithm hashes the "atomic environment" within a radius $r$ centered on each atom, converting it into integer indices recorded in a bit string.
%[text] A radius of 2 (ECFP4) captures substructures up to 2 bonds away from each atom (the diameter 4 is the origin of the name ECFP**4**).
%[text] The bit count of 2048 is set to keep the probability of different substructures colliding into the same bit sufficiently low.
%[text] This fingerprint is independent of the 3D shape of the molecule, so the same structure yields the same bit string even when rotated or flipped.
%[text] **When Descriptor-Based is Suitable:** When physical properties like solubility or absorption define similarity (formulation, ADMET)
%[text] **When Fingerprint is Suitable:** When scaffold or substructure similarity is important (SAR, drug discovery chemistry)
logSection("A02", "Section 1: Morgan Fingerprint Calculation for All Molecules", "Analytics L3"); %[output:969f8f39]
DATA_FILE = "data/list/everyday_chemicals.csv";
FP_RADIUS = 2;     % Morgan radius 2 = ECFP4
FP_NBITS  = 2048;
rawTbl = readtable(DATA_FILE, TextType="string");
nRaw   = height(rawTbl);
logInfo("Loaded %d molecules from %s", nRaw, DATA_FILE); %[output:123f8139]
%[text] Parse SMILES and calculate fingerprints.
fps   = cell(1, nRaw);
valid = false(1, nRaw);
for k = 1:nRaw
    try
        mol     = emk.mol.fromSmiles(rawTbl.SMILES(k));
        fps{k}  = emk.fingerprint.morgan(mol, Radius=FP_RADIUS, NBits=FP_NBITS);
        valid(k) = true;
    catch ME
        logWarn("Skipping %s: %s", rawTbl.CommonName(k), ME.message);
    end
end
validIdx  = find(valid);
validFps  = fps(validIdx);
molNames  = rawTbl.CommonName(validIdx);
molCats   = rawTbl.Category(validIdx);
nMols     = numel(validIdx);
logInfo("ECFP4 fingerprint calculation complete: %d / %d molecules (%d bits)", ... %[output:group:2058d83d] %[output:34124459]
    nMols, nRaw, FP_NBITS); %[output:group:2058d83d] %[output:34124459]
%%
%[text] ## Section 2: Construction of Tanimoto Similarity Matrix
%[text] With ECFP4 fingerprints in hand, we now compute pairwise Tanimoto similarities for all molecular pairs and arrange them in an $N \\times N$ matrix.
%[text] ### Tanimoto (Jaccard) Coefficient
%[text] For binary fingerprints $A$ and $B$, the Tanimoto coefficient is
%[text]{"align":"center"} $T(A,B) = \\frac{c}{a + b - c}$
%[text] where $a$ and $b$ denote the number of on-bits in $A$ and $B$, respectively, and $c$ is the count of bits that are on in both.
%[text] When molecules have identical fingerprints, $T = 1.0$, and when there are no common on-bits, $T = 0.0$.
%[text] In the code, we compute the $N \\times N$ similarity matrix at once using `emk.similarity.matrix(validFps, Metric="tanimoto")`, and convert it to a distance matrix with `distMat = 1 - simMat`.
%[text] The Tanimoto distance $d = 1 - T$ is a formal distance metric satisfying the triangle inequality and can be used as input for the `linkage()` function later.
%[text] **Industry Benchmark:** $T \\geq 0.85$ is nearly identical, $T \\geq 0.70$ is a close analog, $T \\geq 0.40$ is the same chemical class, $T \< 0.40$ is structurally diverse.
logSection("A02", "Section 2: Construction of Tanimoto Similarity Matrix", "Analytics L3"); %[output:20654ff4]
simMat  = emk.similarity.matrix(validFps, Metric="tanimoto");  % N x N double
distMat = 1 - simMat;                                          % Distance matrix
%[text] Set diagonal elements precisely to 0 (to counter numerical noise in Python IPC).
distMat(logical(eye(nMols))) = 0;
logInfo("Similarity matrix: %d x %d (range: %.3f - %.3f)", ... %[output:group:8ac149c8] %[output:13a21c5d]
    nMols, nMols, min(simMat(:)), max(simMat(~logical(eye(nMols))))); %[output:group:8ac149c8] %[output:13a21c5d]
%[text] Visualize the similarity matrix as a heatmap.
figure("Name", "A02 Tanimoto Similarity Matrix"); %[output:7b14a2ce]
imagesc(simMat); %[output:7b14a2ce]
colormap(parula); %[output:7b14a2ce]
colorbar; %[output:7b14a2ce]
clim([0 1]); %[output:7b14a2ce]
title("All-to-All Tanimoto Similarity (ECFP4)"); %[output:7b14a2ce]
xlabel("Molecule Index"); %[output:7b14a2ce]
ylabel("Molecule Index"); %[output:7b14a2ce]
%[text] Sorting by category and overlaying dividing lines makes groups visually distinguishable.
[sortedCats, sortOrd] = sort(molCats);
logInfo("Displayed heatmap of %d x %d similarity matrix", nMols, nMols); %[output:3c97d121]
%%
%[text] ## Section 3: Hierarchical Clustering and Dendrogram
%[text] With the pairwise distance matrix ready, we apply hierarchical clustering using $1 - T$ as the molecular distance, building the full merge tree before deciding where to cut.
%[text] ### Hierarchical Clustering (Ward Linkage Method)
%[text] Hierarchical clustering constructs a tree (dendrogram) by repeating the following steps in a bottom-up manner.
%[text] 1. Initially, each molecule forms its own cluster.
%[text] 2. The two closest clusters are merged based on a linkage criterion.
%[text] 3. Repeat until all molecules form a single cluster. \
%[text] The linkage criterion is the rule for defining "distance between clusters."
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Linkage Method | Characteristics |
%[text] | --- | --- |
%[text] | single (nearest neighbor) | Prone to chain effect |
%[text] | complete (farthest neighbor) | Resistant to outliers |
%[text] | average (UPGMA) | Average distance of all pairs |
%[text] | ward | Minimizes within-cluster variance (chosen in this script) |
%[text:table]
%[text] The Ward linkage method minimizes the within-cluster sum of squares (WCSS), producing compact and evenly sized clusters.
%[text] This objective function is shared with k-means, which is why the two methods often yield similar results.
%[text] ### How to Read a Dendrogram
%[text] The axis of the dendrogram (Ward distance) indicates the "dissimilarity" when two clusters are merged.
%[text] Drawing a horizontal cut line at height $h$ results in $k$ clusters, where $k$ is the number of branches crossed by the line.
%[text] Molecule groups merged at lower heights are structurally very similar.
%[text] In the code, `squareform(distMat, "tovector")` converts the distance matrix to a condensed form (upper triangular vector) before passing it to `linkage()`.
logSection("A02", "Section 3: Hierarchical Clustering and Dendrogram", "Analytics L3"); %[output:7c41f94a]
%[text] Convert the symmetric distance matrix to a condensed vector (upper triangular) required by the MATLAB linkage() function.
condDist = squareform(distMat, "tovector");
Z_tree = linkage(condDist, "ward");
%[text] Plot the dendrogram.
figure("Name", "A02 Hierarchical Clustering Dendrogram"); %[output:93ef2a4d]
D = dendrogram(Z_tree, 0, ... %[output:93ef2a4d]
    Labels=cellstr(molNames), ... %[output:93ef2a4d]
    Orientation="left", ... %[output:93ef2a4d]
    ColorThreshold=0.65 * max(Z_tree(:, 3)));  % 65% of maximum height %[output:93ef2a4d]
title("Ward Linkage Dendrogram  -- Household Chemicals (ECFP4)"); %[output:93ef2a4d]
xlabel("Ward Distance"); %[output:93ef2a4d]
set(gca, FontSize=7); %[output:93ef2a4d]
logInfo("Dendrogram displayed"); %[output:33e6398a]
%[text] Cut at 65% of maximum height and assign cluster labels (approximately 7-8 clusters).
CUT_HEIGHT   = 0.65 * max(Z_tree(:, 3));
clusterLabels_hier = cluster(Z_tree, Cutoff=CUT_HEIGHT, Criterion="distance");
nClusters_hier = max(clusterLabels_hier);
logInfo("Hierarchical cut: threshold=%.3f -> %d clusters", CUT_HEIGHT, nClusters_hier); %[output:0a2a6348]
for c = 1:nClusters_hier %[output:group:6c47d5eb]
    members = molNames(clusterLabels_hier == c);
    logInfo("  Cluster H%d (%d molecules): %s", c, numel(members), ... %[output:72c35d30]
        strjoin(members, ", ")); %[output:72c35d30]
end %[output:group:6c47d5eb]
%%
%[text] ## Section 4: K-means Clustering on Fingerprint Bit Vectors
%[text] Hierarchical clustering builds the entire merge tree first and cuts it later. K-means takes the opposite approach: you specify $k$ upfront, and the algorithm partitions directly into $k$ groups.
%[text] ### How K-means Works
%[text] K-means divides $N$ points into $k$ clusters by repeating the following steps until convergence.
%[text] 1. Assign each point to the nearest centroid.
%[text] 2. Update the centroid as the mean of each cluster.
%[text] 3. Repeat until the centroids no longer move. \
%[text] Standard k-means uses Euclidean distance, but Hamming distance (proportion of differing bits) is suitable for binary fingerprints.
%[text] You can specify this with the `kmeans()` option `Distance="hamming"`.
%[text] ### Choosing $k$: The Elbow Method
%[text] Increasing $k$ monotonically decreases the within-cluster sum of squares (WCSS), but the rate of decrease sharply drops after a certain $k$.
%[text] The "elbow" point marks the inherent number of clusters in the data.
%[text] In the code, `kmeans()` is executed for each $k$, and the total of the return value `sumd` (WCSS for each cluster) is recorded.
%[text] Convert fingerprints to a numerical bit matrix ($N \\times$ FP\_NBITS).
logSection("A02", "Section 4: K-means Clustering on Fingerprint Bit Vectors", "Analytics L3"); %[output:97c19ca3]
bitMat = zeros(nMols, FP_NBITS, "logical");
for j = 1:nMols
    bitMat(j, :) = emk.fingerprint.toArray(validFps{j});
end
bitMat_double = double(bitMat);
logInfo("Fingerprint bit matrix: %d x %d", size(bitMat_double)); %[output:1ed09498]
%[text] Elbow Method: Evaluate WCSS for k = 2 to 8.
K_MAX = 8;
wcss  = zeros(1, K_MAX);     % Within-cluster sum of squares
rng(42);   % For reproducibility
for k = 2:K_MAX
    [~, ~, sumd] = kmeans(bitMat_double, k, ...
        Distance="hamming", Replicates=5, Display="off");
    wcss(k) = sum(sumd);
end
figure("Name", "A02 K-Means Elbow Curve"); %[output:8e6c2194]
plot(2:K_MAX, wcss(2:K_MAX), "-o", Color=[0.2 0.5 0.8], LineWidth=1.5); %[output:8e6c2194]
xlabel("Number of Clusters k"); %[output:8e6c2194]
ylabel("Within-cluster Sum of Squares"); %[output:8e6c2194]
title("Elbow Method  -- K-Means on ECFP4 Bit Vectors"); %[output:8e6c2194]
grid on; %[output:8e6c2194]
logInfo("Displayed the elbow curve (looking for the point where the sharp drop flattens out)"); %[output:71997565]
%%
%[text] ## Section 5: Silhouette Analysis for Selecting k
%[text] The elbow method narrows the candidate values of $k$; silhouette analysis provides a quantitative score to pick the best one.
%[text] ### Silhouette Coefficient
%[text] The silhouette coefficient $s(i)$ quantifies how well molecule $i$ fits its assigned cluster relative to the next-best alternative.
%[text]{"align":"center"} $s(i) = \\frac{b(i) - a(i)}{\\max(a(i),\\ b(i))}$
%[text] Here, $a(i)$ denotes the mean distance from molecule $i$ to all other members of its cluster (intra-cluster cohesion), and $b(i)$ the mean distance to the nearest neighboring cluster (inter-cluster separation).
%[text] If $s(i) \\approx 1$, the molecule is well-clustered.
%[text] If $s(i) \\approx 0$, the molecule is near the boundary between two clusters.
%[text] If $s(i) \\approx -1$, it may be assigned to the wrong cluster.
%[text] The $k$ that maximizes the average silhouette $\\bar{s}$ for all molecules is the optimal number of clusters for this data.
%[text] In the code, `silhouette(bitMat_double, labels_k, "hamming")` calculates the silhouette coefficient for each molecule, and the average is plotted for each $k$.
logSection("A02", "Section 5: Silhouette Analysis for Selecting k", "Analytics L3"); %[output:860f84ce]
silScores = zeros(1, K_MAX);
rng(42);
for k = 2:K_MAX
    labels_k = kmeans(bitMat_double, k, ...
        Distance="hamming", Replicates=5, Display="off");
    sil = silhouette(bitMat_double, labels_k, "hamming");
    silScores(k) = mean(sil);
end
figure("Name", "A02 Silhouette Score"); %[output:35849a7c]
plot(2:K_MAX, silScores(2:K_MAX), "-s", Color=[0.8 0.3 0.2], LineWidth=1.5); %[output:35849a7c]
xlabel("Number of Clusters k"); %[output:35849a7c]
ylabel("Average Silhouette Score"); %[output:35849a7c]
title("Silhouette Analysis  -- K-Means on ECFP4 Bit Vectors"); %[output:35849a7c]
grid on; %[output:35849a7c]
logInfo("Displayed silhouette plot"); %[output:50c36fcb]
[bestSil, bestK_idx] = max(silScores(2:K_MAX));
bestK = bestK_idx + 1;
logInfo("Optimal k by silhouette: k = %d  (Average Silhouette = %.3f)", bestK, bestSil); %[output:9952a500]
%[text] **Guidelines for Interpreting Silhouette Scores:** $\\bar{s} \\geq 0.70$ indicates a strong cluster structure, $0.50 \\leq \\bar{s} \< 0.70$ indicates a reasonable structure, $0.25 \\leq \\bar{s} \< 0.50$ indicates a weak (but meaningful) structure, and $\\bar{s} \< 0.25$ indicates no substantial structure.
%[text] If the $\\bar{s}$ obtained with the optimal $k$ is below 0.5, it reflects the limitation of squeezing 30 chemically diverse household chemicals into a small number of $k$. Consider trying a larger $k$ or interpret in conjunction with hierarchical clustering results.
%[text] Execute the final k-means using the optimal $k$.
rng(42);
finalLabels_km = kmeans(bitMat_double, bestK, ...
    Distance="hamming", Replicates=10, Display="off");
logInfo("K-Means (k=%d) Final Cluster Assignment:", bestK); %[output:958503da]
for c = 1:bestK %[output:group:887ac4a0]
    members = molNames(finalLabels_km == c);
    logInfo("  Cluster KM%d (%d molecules): %s", c, numel(members), ... %[output:6b4fdcf3]
        strjoin(members, ", ")); %[output:6b4fdcf3]
end %[output:group:887ac4a0]
%[text] **Interpretation of Cluster Bias:** If one cluster contains the majority of molecules, it means structurally diverse molecules are mixed within that cluster, and k-means could not further split them.
%[text] This suggests the data may not have a true $k$ cluster structure and may be continuously distributed. Try increasing $k$ to 6-8, or if silhouette scores remain low, refer to the hierarchical clustering results in Section 3 as a priority.
%%
%[text] ## Section 6: Visualizing Clusters on the Similarity Matrix
%[text] With cluster assignments from both methods in hand, we now reorder the similarity matrix by cluster membership to produce a sorted heatmap -- an intuitive visual check of clustering quality.
%[text] ### Reading Block Structures in a Sorted Heatmap
%[text] When rows and columns are sorted by cluster, molecules within the same group appear adjacent and form bright square blocks along the diagonal. Tight, high-contrast blocks indicate well-separated clusters; diffuse blocks suggest that $k$ may need to be reconsidered or a different linkage method tried.
%[text] In the code, `[~, sortByCluster] = sort(clusterLabels_hier)` produces the sort order, and `simMat(sortByCluster, sortByCluster)` applies it to both axes of the similarity matrix.
logSection("A02", "Section 6: Visualizing Clusters on the Similarity Matrix", "Analytics L3"); %[output:1b7e507c]
[~, sortByCluster] = sort(clusterLabels_hier);
simMatSorted = simMat(sortByCluster, sortByCluster);
namesSorted  = molNames(sortByCluster);
catsSorted   = molCats(sortByCluster);
figure("Name", "A02 Similarity Matrix (Cluster Order Sorted)"); %[output:58520423]
imagesc(simMatSorted); %[output:58520423]
colormap(parula); %[output:58520423]
colorbar; %[output:58520423]
clim([0 1]); %[output:58520423]
title("Similarity Matrix (Hierarchical Cluster Order Sorted)"); %[output:58520423]
xlabel("Molecules (Cluster Order)"); %[output:58520423]
ylabel("Molecules (Cluster Order)"); %[output:58520423]
%[text] Add tick labels (truncated to the first 8 characters).
tick_labels = cellfun(@(n) n(1:min(8,end)), cellstr(namesSorted), ...
    UniformOutput=false);
xticks(1:nMols); xticklabels(tick_labels); xtickangle(90); %[output:58520423]
yticks(1:nMols); yticklabels(tick_labels); %[output:58520423]
set(gca, FontSize=6); %[output:58520423]
%[text] Draw cluster boundaries with white lines to clarify the range of each group.
boundaries = [0; find(diff(clusterLabels_hier(sortByCluster))); nMols] + 0.5;
hold on; %[output:58520423]
for b = boundaries'
    xline(b, "w-", LineWidth=1); %[output:58520423]
    yline(b, "w-", LineWidth=1);
end
hold off; %[output:58520423]
logInfo("Displayed sorted similarity matrix with cluster boundaries"); %[output:1297d29d]
%[text] ## Summary
%[text] - ECFP4 fingerprints encode local substructures around each atom as bit vectors.
%[text] - Tanimoto distance $d = 1 - T$ is used as input for hierarchical clustering.
%[text] - Ward linkage minimizes intra-cluster variance, generating compact and balanced clusters.
%[text] - Silhouette analysis provides a quantitative means to select the optimal $k$ based on data.
%[text] - Sorted heatmaps serve as a visual quality check for block structures. \

